This week, I completed several medium-level challenges in picoCTF including Disk, Disk, Sleuth! II, MacroHard WeakEdge, Matryoshka Doll,
Wireshark doo doo.., Disk, Disk, Sleuth!, tunn3l v1s10n, Wireshark twoo twooo.., Trivial Flag Transfer Protocol, Weird File, Pitter, Patter, 
Platters, shark on wire 2, like1000, What Lies Within, and c0rrupt.

These challenges helped me practice analyzing disk images, recovering hidden files, and investigating network traffic. I used forensic tools 
such as The Sleuth Kit to explore disk artifacts and Wireshark to examine packet captures and reconstruct transmitted data. Some challenges 
also required identifying incorrect file headers, extracting hidden layers from files, and decoding encoded information.

One challenge during the week was recognizing the correct technique to use, especially when files were nested or corrupted. 
However, by carefully analyzing clues and testing different forensic methods, I was able to retrieve the hidden flags.

Overall, these challenges improved my understanding of digital forensics, network packet analysis, and file recovery techniques, while also 
strengthening my problem-solving skills when dealing with hidden or damaged digital evidence.
